The `TestsFromDafny` class is normally generated by `make transpile_java` (specifically the test transpilation step from `RunMain.dfy`). It's a one-liner that calls `WrappedDDBEncryptionMain_Compile.__default.ASDF()`.

You need to run the transpilation step first:

```bash
cd /Users/rishavkj/Documents/Storage/Team-Repos/aws-database-encryption-sdk-dynamodb/TestVectors
make transpile_java
```

This will generate `src/test/dafny-generated/TestsFromDafny.java`. That's the missing piece — the test entry point that `make test_java` expects.

If you don't want to run the full Dafny transpilation (requires Dafny 4.9.0 installed), you can manually create `src/test/dafny-generated/TestsFromDafny.java` with:

```java
public class TestsFromDafny {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    WrappedDDBEncryptionMain_Compile.__default.ASDF();
  }
}
```

That's all it does — it's the test runner entry point that kicks off the `ASDF()` method which loads all the JSON configs and runs all tests.

There it is. The transpilation generates `runtimes/java/TestsFromDafny-java/` and then moves it to `runtimes/java/src/test/dafny-generated/`. 

You ran `transpile_java` which does `transpile_implementation_java` + `transpile_test_java`. The implementation part worked (you have `src/main/dafny-generated/`), but the test part either failed silently or the output got cleaned up.

Just run the test transpilation again:

```bash
cd /Users/rishavkj/Documents/Storage/Team-Repos/aws-database-encryption-sdk-dynamodb/TestVectors
make transpile_test_java
```

Or if you just want to get past this quickly, create the file manually — it's a one-liner that Dafny generates with `--include-test-runner`:

```java
// src/test/dafny-generated/TestsFromDafny.java
public class TestsFromDafny {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    TestWrappedDDBEncryptionMain_Compile.__default.ASDF();
  }
}
```

(The module name is `TestWrappedDDBEncryptionMain` from `RunMain.dfy`)

